<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-08-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-08-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="119" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Adee</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Conger</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-08-23"><hi rend="italic">August 23,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Adee states that the consul-general at Shanghai has been telegraphed
                            that he is not to commit himself to any theory that the United States
                            could be called upon by China or by the foreign consuls to guarantee
                            Chinese neutrality, and that he is to safeguard only as far as possible
                            xlmerican neutral interests if threatened, and to avoid all indications
                            of general policy. Utmost circumspection required.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>